docs.abstract: Even as the court’s center of gravity shifted to the right, the court’s more liberal justices held their own.
docs.snippet: Even as the court’s center of gravity shifted to the right, the court’s more liberal justices held their own.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court term that ended on Thursday was expected to be a blood bath for its four-member liberal wing. Instead, shifting alliances produced a series of surprising liberal victories. Some were minor, and some were tentative.

headline.main: A Supreme Court Term Marked by Shifting Alliances and Surprise Votes
headline.print_headline: A Term Marked by Shifting Alliances and Surprise Votes.

byline.original: By Adam Liptak and Alicia Parlapiano

docs.abstract: Over the last month, Justice Sonia Sotomayor has issued three opinions describing flaws in the capital justice system.
docs.snippet: Over the last month, Justice Sonia Sotomayor has issued three opinions describing flaws in the capital justice system.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The terse Supreme Court rulings arrived in the evening, in time to allow an execution later that night. There were three rulings in the last month or so, at 5:52 p.m., at 7:01 p.m. and at 10:13 p.m. They were bland and formulaic, saying only that the court had denied an “application for stay of execution of sentence of death.” The inmates who had filed the applications were put to death within hours.

headline.main: In Death Penalty Cases, Sotomayor Is Alone in ‘Bearing Witness’
headline.print_headline: For Sotomayor, No Death Penalty Case Is Routine

docs.abstract: The decision featured unusual alliances, with Justices Clarence Thomas and Neil M. Gorsuch joining three of the court’s more liberal members.
docs.snippet: The decision featured unusual alliances, with Justices Clarence Thomas and Neil M. Gorsuch joining three of the court’s more liberal members.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Monday dismissed a challenge to the voting map for Virginia’s House of Delegates, saying that state lawmakers were not entitled to appeal a ruling striking down parts of the map on race-discrimination grounds. The Supreme Court’s action is likely to help Democrats in elections this fall.

headline.main: Justices Dismiss Appeal in Virginia Racial Gerrymandering Case
headline.print_headline: With Ruling, Voting Maps Stay in Place In Virginia

docs.abstract: In a friend-of-the-court brief, the department urged the justices to hear the president’s appeal in a clash with Manhattan prosecutors.
docs.snippet: In a friend-of-the-court brief, the department urged the justices to hear the president’s appeal in a clash with Manhattan prosecutors.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Justice Department filed a friend-of-the-court brief on Friday urging the Supreme Court to hear President Trump’s appeal seeking to keep his financial records private. Mr. Trump is trying to block a subpoena from Manhattan prosecutors that would require his accounting firm to turn over eight years of his personal and corporate tax returns.

headline.main: Justice Dept. Urges Supreme Court to Back Trump in Tax Records Case

docs.abstract: In its first full term since the arrival of Justice Kavanaugh, the court could issue a number of blockbuster decisions on divisive issues in an election year.
docs.snippet: In its first full term since the arrival of Justice Kavanaugh, the court could issue a number of blockbuster decisions on divisive issues in an election year.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court returns to the bench on Monday to start a term that will be studded with major cases on gay and transgender rights, immigration, abortion, guns and religion. The rulings will arrive by June, in the midst of an already divisive presidential campaign.

headline.main: As the Supreme Court Gets Back to Work, Five Big Cases to Watch
headline.print_headline: As the Supreme Court Gets Back to Work, Five Big Cases to Watch

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Abortion rights are at risk at the Supreme Court, but the short-term threat may not come from extreme measures like the one passed by Alabama lawmakers.

headline.main: Alabama Aims Squarely at Roe, but the Supreme Court May Prefer Glancing Blows
headline.print_headline: Path to Nullify Roe v. Wade a Little Bit at a Time

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Justice John Paul Stevens, who died on Tuesday at 99, served for almost 35 years on the Supreme Court until his retirement in 2010. Here are some highlights from that long and eventful run.
